>
  <p>
    Buy or inherit a property with a septic system that's been in the ground for decades, and you'll
    often find the same thing: a system that works, and a folder that's empty. Where's the tank? When
    was it last pumped? What's been repaired? Reconstructing that history — or building it from
    scratch — is genuinely worthwhile, because knowing where the tank is and what shape it's in makes
    every future service faster, cheaper, and less of a guessing game.
  </p>

  {/* Intended asset: /images/resources/how-to-find-septic-records-and-tank-locations-hero.webp — see public/images/resources/README.md */}
